    <hgroup>
      <h1 id="id_title">Steve Jobs Originally Planned iPad With Intel Inside, Biography Says</h1>
      <h2 id="id_deck"></h2>
      <div class="byline"><address>
          <span id="id_author">By Peter Pachal</span>
        </address>
        <span class="sep"></span> <time datetime="2011-10-26T22:29:00+05:30">Oct. 26, 2011, 10:29 p.m.</time>
        
        <div class="sharer" id="enhancedsharer">
         <script src="/s/pcmag/social-share.js?406" id="sharer-widget-js" data-position="left" data-linkedin data-facebook data-twitter data-pinterest data-reddir defer></script>
        </div>
        
      </div>
    </hgroup>


    
    <div class="splashImg" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/ImageObject">
    <img src="https://sm.pcmag.com/t/pcmag_in/news/s/steve-jobs/steve-jobs-originally-planned-ipad-with-intel-insi_egvr.1920.jpg" srcset="https://sm.pcmag.com/t/pcmag_in/news/s/steve-jobs/steve-jobs-originally-planned-ipad-with-intel-insi_egvr.1920.jpg 1x, https://sm.pcmag.com/t/pcmag_in/news/s/steve-jobs/steve-jobs-originally-planned-ipad-with-intel-insi_egvr.3840.jpg 2x" align="left" alt="" itemprop="image">
    </div>

</div>


<div class="wfull">

</div>

<div class="wrapper content">
    <div id="content">
        
  <article class="article">
    <div id="id_text">
    <p>Although Apple gets chips for its entire Mac lineup from Intel, <a class="" href="http://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,2395195,00.asp">Steve Jobs</a> had issues with the company, Walter Isaacson reveals in <a class="" href="http://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,2395246,00.asp">his biography</a> of the former Apple CEO. Jobs thought Intel was a company that was slow to adapt, although at one point Jobs had considered using Intel technology in the iPhone and iPad.</p>
<p>Apple made the high-profile switch to Intel chips in the middle of the last decade after a long period of using IBM's and Motorola's PowerPC processors. Intel now powers all the desktops and laptops Apple makes. And if things had been different, it might be in Apple's iOS devices, too.</p><div class="article_ads mrec1"><div class="zad halfpage" data-zadtype="halfpage" data-suffix="ATF_mpu"></div></div></p>
<p>In the early days of the partnership, Isaacson writes, Jobs had plans to power the iPad with an Intel Atom chip, even though one of his key executives, Tony Fadell (who helped create the iPod and went on to found a company that just announced a <a class="" href="http://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,2395108,00.asp">high-tech thermostat</a>) thought Apple should go with a processor based on the ARM architecture, the low-power design that's the basis of almost every chip in cell phones and tablets today.</p><div class="galleryPreview" id="gallery41787"><a class="galleryPreview" href="http://in.pcmag.com/desktop/41787/gallery/the-greatest-victories-of-steve-jobs?p=1" style="background-image: url('http://im.ziffdavisinternational.com/t/pcmag_in/photo/t/the-apple-/the-apple-i_xnvt.200.jpg')"></a><a class="galleryPreview" href="http://in.pcmag.com/desktop/41787/gallery/the-greatest-victories-of-steve-jobs?p=2" style="background-image: url('http://im.ziffdavisinternational.com/t/pcmag_in/photo/1/1984-mac-c/1984-mac-commercial_z4st.200.jpg')"></a><a class="galleryPreview" href="http://in.pcmag.com/desktop/41787/gallery/the-greatest-victories-of-steve-jobs?p=3" style="background-image: url('http://im.ziffdavisinternational.com/t/pcmag_in/photo/a/apple-maci/apple-macintosh_pute.200.jpg')"></a><a class="galleryPreview" href="http://in.pcmag.com/desktop/41787/gallery/the-greatest-victories-of-steve-jobs?p=4" style="background-image: url('http://im.ziffdavisinternational.com/t/pcmag_in/photo/s/steve-jobs/steve-jobs-returns_sgz1.200.jpg')"></a><a class="galleryPreview" href="http://in.pcmag.com/desktop/41787/gallery/the-greatest-victories-of-steve-jobs?p=5" style="background-image: url('http://im.ziffdavisinternational.com/t/pcmag_in/photo/t/the-imac/the-imac_dh9x.200.jpg')"></a><a class="galleryPreview" href="http://in.pcmag.com/desktop/41787/gallery/the-greatest-victories-of-steve-jobs?p=6" style="background-image: url('http://im.ziffdavisinternational.com/t/pcmag_in/photo/t/the-ipod/the-ipod_kc2x.200.jpg')"></a><a class="galleryGoto" href="/desktop/41787/gallery/the-greatest-victories-of-steve-jobs">View all Photos in Gallery</a></div><p></p>
<p>"At the high-performance end, Intel is the best," Jobs said. "At the beginning, we were doing wonderful things together. They wanted this big joint project to do chips for future iPhones."</p>
<p>Ultimately, though, Fadell's point of view won out. Apple acquired a couple of chip companies, PA Semi and Intrinsity, and created its own chips, the A4 and later A5. Jobs explains why he didn't go with Intel for the iPad and iPhone in the book.</p>
<p>"There were two reasons we did not go with them" he said. "One was that they are just really slow. They are like a steamship, not very flexible. We are used to going pretty fast. Second is that we just did not want to teach them everything, which they could go and sell to our competitors,"</p>
<p>Jobs also voiced other criticisms. He said Intel's "graphics suck" and that its processors don't have the same system-on-a-chip efficiencies of the A4/A5. It's not known if the interview was conducted before the most recent refresh of the MacBook Air, which switched from Nvidia graphics to Intel and include Intel's energy-efficient "Sandy Bridge" processors. Intel also has plans to expand its system-on-a-chip offerings, including designs for <a class="internal" href="http://in.pcmag.com/news/26327/next-generation-of-windows-will-run-on-arm">Windows 8</a>.</p>
<p>Isaacson goes on to quote Intel CEO Paul Otellini, who says part of the reason Intel did not appear on the iPad was because the companies could not agree on pricing, and because Jobs wanted too much control over the final design of the iPad chip.<ziffhtml id="3778"><ziffhtml id="3748"></ziffhtml></ziffhtml></p>
    </div>
    
  </article>

    </div>
    
